1
00:00:04,637 --> 00:00:05,572
<i>Hey.</i>

2
00:00:06,506 --> 00:00:08,074
<i>Have you kissed anyone before?</i>

3
00:00:22,355 --> 00:00:23,223
<i>That day,</i>

4
00:00:24,958 --> 00:00:26,793
<i>the four of us committed a crime.</i>

5
00:00:27,360 --> 00:00:28,795
<i>The crime we committed</i>

6
00:00:30,063 --> 00:00:33,333
<i>was sealed away in a time capsule</i>
<i>that would never be opened in the future.</i>

7
00:00:33,400 --> 00:00:37,203
<i>Your son shoplifted from my store.</i>

8
00:00:37,270 --> 00:00:39,672
<i>The victim is Hideyuki Sakuma,</i>
<i>40 years old.</i>

9
00:00:40,240 --> 00:00:41,207
Smile Sakuma…

10
00:00:41,274 --> 00:00:43,143
It's believed that Oshima's accomplice

11
00:00:43,209 --> 00:00:44,944
took the 30 million yen

12
00:00:45,011 --> 00:00:47,013
<i>and Officer Kiyohara's gun,</i>

13
00:00:47,080 --> 00:00:48,581
<i>but the 30 million yen and the gun</i>

14
00:00:49,082 --> 00:00:50,450
<i>- were never found…</i>
<i>- The question is,</i>

15
00:00:51,117 --> 00:00:52,952
<i>who shot Oshima?</i>

16
00:00:54,020 --> 00:00:55,422
I shot him.

17
00:00:57,490 --> 00:00:59,459
<i>I don't think I deserve to be happy.</i>

18
00:00:59,526 --> 00:01:00,994
<i>I can't undo the fact…</i>

19
00:01:02,162 --> 00:01:04,030
<i>that I have committed a crime.</i>

20
00:01:05,198 --> 00:01:06,766
Maki.

21
00:01:06,833 --> 00:01:09,702
<i>That day,</i>
<i>I went to Sakuma's place by myself</i>

22
00:01:10,303 --> 00:01:12,305
<i>because that was the only option I had.</i>

23
00:01:23,249 --> 00:01:24,584
Where's the gun?

24
00:01:25,218 --> 00:01:26,052
Sorry.

25
00:01:26,119 --> 00:01:29,656
<i>Where's the gun? Where's the damn gun?!</i>

26
00:01:36,896 --> 00:01:40,800
<i>I shot the manager of Smile Sakuma</i>
<i>with a gun.</i>

27
00:01:43,570 --> 00:01:44,604
<i>I knew</i>

28
00:01:45,405 --> 00:01:47,574
<i>you'd bring the gun to me.</i>

29
00:01:49,375 --> 00:01:50,543
Detective Tobina,

30
00:01:51,711 --> 00:01:55,248
there's a chance you didn't kill Oshima.

31
00:01:56,282 --> 00:01:58,952
We'll find that out
once we examine this gun.

32
00:02:04,858 --> 00:02:07,160
You retrieved the gun to help Junichi?

33
00:02:47,867 --> 00:02:48,768
Oh.

34
00:02:50,770 --> 00:02:52,839
I just thought of a great title.

35
00:02:54,641 --> 00:02:57,443
Deep breathing is important.

36
00:03:01,214 --> 00:03:03,216
Oh man, that was close,
I wasn't breathing.

37
00:03:03,283 --> 00:03:05,718
Don't stop. Take a deep breath.

38
00:03:05,785 --> 00:03:07,320
Breathe. Deeply.

39
00:03:10,490 --> 00:03:12,192
It feels great.

40
00:03:12,258 --> 00:03:15,261
I forgot I have to take a deep breath
when I feel out of sorts.

41
00:03:15,328 --> 00:03:16,863
The body feels stiff, huh?

42
00:03:16,930 --> 00:03:19,332
<i>That's right, that's right</i>

43
00:03:20,133 --> 00:03:21,668
- It's a bath time song.
- Ms. Nara.

44
00:03:27,173 --> 00:03:28,107
Ms. Nara.

45
00:03:28,641 --> 00:03:30,009
Please close the door.

46
00:03:51,130 --> 00:03:52,198
What's going on?

47
00:03:54,934 --> 00:03:55,935
Right now,

48
00:03:58,104 --> 00:04:00,173
I'm going to check

49
00:04:01,941 --> 00:04:04,911
how many bullets are left in this gun.

50
00:04:05,478 --> 00:04:06,546
And that

51
00:04:07,513 --> 00:04:10,049
may reveal some new truths.

52
00:04:42,415 --> 00:04:44,450
There are three bullets remaining.

53
00:04:52,292 --> 00:04:53,326
Detective Tobina,

54
00:04:54,227 --> 00:04:57,864
we won't even discuss whether the bullet
you fired really hit Oshima or not,

55
00:04:58,498 --> 00:04:59,399
because you

56
00:05:00,400 --> 00:05:02,402
didn't even fire the gun.

57
00:05:04,370 --> 00:05:05,204
What?

58
00:05:05,772 --> 00:05:08,107
You were a sixth-grader at the time,

59
00:05:08,641 --> 00:05:12,779
and you had just discovered
the body of Officer Kiyohara,

60
00:05:12,845 --> 00:05:14,881
so you were in a state of shock.

61
00:05:17,050 --> 00:05:19,786
When a gunshot rang out nearby,

62
00:05:19,852 --> 00:05:23,189
you assumed it was you who had fired it.

63
00:05:24,657 --> 00:05:26,559
Is that not possible?

64
00:05:37,437 --> 00:05:39,572
Detective Inoue,
I'm going to borrow your car.

65
00:05:39,639 --> 00:05:40,473
Where are you going?

66
00:05:41,774 --> 00:05:42,942
Prefectural police headquarters.

67
00:05:46,946 --> 00:05:48,214
I'm Nagai.

68
00:05:48,281 --> 00:05:49,849
MITSUBA POLICE STATION

69
00:05:54,554 --> 00:05:56,322
Keisuke, you're okay with all this?

70
00:05:57,357 --> 00:05:58,991
Of course I'm not okay.

71
00:06:02,128 --> 00:06:04,964
When Masaki asked about Makiko
I didn't know what to say.

72
00:06:05,031 --> 00:06:07,166
I'll be here to protect you, Masaki.

73
00:06:08,968 --> 00:06:10,069
What about Mom?

74
00:06:12,472 --> 00:06:13,539
She'll be all right.

75
00:06:13,606 --> 00:06:15,041
We'll be with her.

76
00:06:15,541 --> 00:06:17,977
<i>But Junichi answered in an instant.</i>

77
00:06:19,312 --> 00:06:20,747
I was hit with the reality.

78
00:06:21,714 --> 00:06:24,050
I knew then I could never beat Junichi.

79
00:06:27,120 --> 00:06:28,388
It pissed me off too.

80
00:06:29,088 --> 00:06:33,192
As Masaki's father I wanted to be cool,
but I ended up looking pathetic.

81
00:06:33,259 --> 00:06:35,094
You can turn the tables in no time.

82
00:06:35,728 --> 00:06:39,732
You said you'd have Maki's mother help out
until Maki comes back,

83
00:06:40,566 --> 00:06:42,835
but wouldn't it be better for Masaki
to live with you?

84
00:06:44,270 --> 00:06:45,271
Oh…

85
00:06:46,072 --> 00:06:47,774
- Well…
- What? You can't?

86
00:06:52,278 --> 00:06:54,013
I hadn't told you yet, but…

87
00:06:56,816 --> 00:06:58,484
I remarried.

88
00:07:04,357 --> 00:07:05,191
When?

89
00:07:05,858 --> 00:07:07,059
A year ago.

90
00:07:09,162 --> 00:07:11,063
We're having a baby soon too.

91
00:07:14,867 --> 00:07:16,402
Maki didn't tell me about this.

92
00:07:16,469 --> 00:07:18,805
Makiko only found out recently.

93
00:07:21,607 --> 00:07:22,442
What?

94
00:07:29,415 --> 00:07:31,451
MITSUBA POLICE STATION

95
00:07:31,517 --> 00:07:32,685
<i>Makiko Iwamoto</i>

96
00:07:32,752 --> 00:07:35,321
has turned herself in
and admitted to killing Sakuma.

97
00:07:35,388 --> 00:07:38,291
The questioning will begin soon.

98
00:07:38,791 --> 00:07:40,126
<i>And the gun?</i>

99
00:07:40,927 --> 00:07:42,762
<i>The police confiscated it.</i>

100
00:07:43,262 --> 00:07:44,130
<i>I see.</i>

101
00:07:44,697 --> 00:07:47,800
I guess this wraps up this case.

102
00:07:47,867 --> 00:07:48,868
CHIEF KOSUGI

103
00:07:48,935 --> 00:07:50,136
<i>You're testifying</i>

104
00:07:51,637 --> 00:07:54,273
that when you refused his request for sex,

105
00:07:55,274 --> 00:07:56,876
he threatened you with a gun,

106
00:07:58,578 --> 00:07:59,979
and while you two fought,

107
00:08:00,980 --> 00:08:02,815
you picked up the gun

108
00:08:04,517 --> 00:08:07,320
and fired it when he came towards you.

109
00:08:09,021 --> 00:08:10,490
Is that correct?

110
00:08:13,626 --> 00:08:14,494
Yes.

111
00:08:17,196 --> 00:08:18,598
It's an unfortunate incident.

112
00:08:21,501 --> 00:08:23,436
You had no intention of killing him,

113
00:08:24,504 --> 00:08:26,539
but it just happened by accident.

114
00:08:28,307 --> 00:08:29,175
No.

115
00:08:30,343 --> 00:08:31,844
<i>Do you finally remember</i>

116
00:08:32,678 --> 00:08:33,779
<i>who I am?</i>

117
00:08:36,415 --> 00:08:38,985
This is fate.

118
00:08:41,754 --> 00:08:45,625
But I find that impertinent attitude
irresistible.

119
00:08:47,827 --> 00:08:49,095
<i>At that moment,</i>

120
00:08:52,632 --> 00:08:54,901
I had murderous intent.

121
00:09:01,107 --> 00:09:02,408
I would also

122
00:09:03,609 --> 00:09:05,411
want to kill someone

123
00:09:07,113 --> 00:09:10,550
who hurt me or someone I care about.

124
00:09:19,892 --> 00:09:20,893
Oh,

125
00:09:21,794 --> 00:09:23,663
after examining that gun,

126
00:09:24,497 --> 00:09:27,233
we found out that Detective Tobina
did not shoot anyone.

127
00:09:49,989 --> 00:09:51,524
This is what makes you cry?

128
00:09:57,363 --> 00:09:58,598
I see.

129
00:10:01,701 --> 00:10:02,835
You

130
00:10:03,669 --> 00:10:07,139
wanted to free Detective Tobina
from the guilt of murder.

131
00:10:08,507 --> 00:10:10,743
You wished to help him out
that badly, huh?

132
00:10:12,211 --> 00:10:13,279
But now

133
00:10:14,513 --> 00:10:17,516
you're going to be carrying
the guilt of murdering someone.

134
00:10:35,601 --> 00:10:36,602
She's ready.

135
00:10:42,208 --> 00:10:45,578
I'll be here all night, okay?

136
00:10:54,620 --> 00:10:56,255
KOTONO

137
00:10:59,425 --> 00:11:00,359
Sorry.

138
00:11:03,529 --> 00:11:04,363
What's wrong?

139
00:11:04,430 --> 00:11:06,032
My water broke.

140
00:11:06,098 --> 00:11:07,033
What?

141
00:11:07,633 --> 00:11:09,135
<i>I called the hospital</i>

142
00:11:09,669 --> 00:11:11,003
<i>and they told me to come right away.</i>

143
00:11:12,238 --> 00:11:13,673
Keisuke,

144
00:11:14,407 --> 00:11:15,708
where are you right now?

145
00:11:15,775 --> 00:11:18,344
Sorry, I'm in Mitsuba right now.

146
00:11:19,245 --> 00:11:20,279
<i>I…</i>

147
00:11:20,913 --> 00:11:22,648
<i>I need to call a taxi, huh?</i>

148
00:11:23,215 --> 00:11:25,384
- Can you call for a taxi?
- Okay, microwave.

149
00:11:25,451 --> 00:11:26,452
<i>Yeah.</i>

150
00:11:26,519 --> 00:11:28,788
- Two and a half minutes.
- I'll be there as soon as I can.

151
00:11:28,854 --> 00:11:29,755
Approximately.

152
00:11:30,456 --> 00:11:31,590
Bye.

153
00:11:32,324 --> 00:11:35,127
- Write, "It's <i>chikuzenni."</i>
- It's <i>chikuzenni.</i>

154
00:11:35,695 --> 00:11:37,096
My wife's water broke.

155
00:11:40,533 --> 00:11:41,901
Such bad timing.

156
00:11:42,468 --> 00:11:44,236
You should hurry up and go.

157
00:11:45,771 --> 00:11:47,073
I'll keep an eye on Masaki.

158
00:11:47,740 --> 00:11:48,708
Thanks.

159
00:11:59,919 --> 00:12:01,120
- Here.
- Okay.

160
00:12:04,957 --> 00:12:06,325
Hiromi.

161
00:12:06,392 --> 00:12:07,226
Thanks for everything.

162
00:12:10,296 --> 00:12:11,764
I'll stay here tonight.

163
00:12:13,532 --> 00:12:14,767
Okay.

164
00:12:15,334 --> 00:12:16,802
- Here.
- Thanks.

165
00:12:42,428 --> 00:12:44,263
Mom went to the police

166
00:12:46,565 --> 00:12:48,300
because she killed the supermarket guy?

167
00:12:51,670 --> 00:12:52,938
It is, right?

168
00:13:15,361 --> 00:13:16,629
Why did she kill him?

169
00:13:23,836 --> 00:13:25,938
She did something very bad, right?

170
00:13:35,381 --> 00:13:36,415
Mom

171
00:13:37,416 --> 00:13:39,385
told me not to bully people,

172
00:13:41,754 --> 00:13:43,222
so why did she kill him?

173
00:13:47,259 --> 00:13:48,527
How can she do something

174
00:13:49,929 --> 00:13:51,430
so awful?

175
00:13:54,567 --> 00:13:57,002
Hey! Tell me why!

176
00:14:09,014 --> 00:14:09,915
Masaki.

177
00:14:15,855 --> 00:14:17,122
Do you love your mom?

178
00:14:18,757 --> 00:14:20,092
I don't like

179
00:14:21,327 --> 00:14:22,695
murderers.

180
00:14:27,199 --> 00:14:28,500
I hate

181
00:14:29,501 --> 00:14:30,769
Mom.

182
00:14:31,503 --> 00:14:32,905
She's the worst.

183
00:14:52,858 --> 00:14:54,827
It's because I shoplifted.

184
00:14:56,095 --> 00:14:58,063
It's all my fault.

185
00:14:59,732 --> 00:15:03,402
It's all because I shoplifted.

186
00:15:13,779 --> 00:15:16,081
It's because I shoplifted.

187
00:15:18,017 --> 00:15:19,118
How's Masaki?

188
00:15:20,052 --> 00:15:21,120
He fell asleep.

189
00:15:21,787 --> 00:15:24,390
I'm glad. I was worried
since I heard him having a breakdown.

190
00:15:26,392 --> 00:15:28,627
Junichi, do you want coffee?

191
00:15:28,694 --> 00:15:29,695
Thanks.

192
00:15:35,167 --> 00:15:36,702
By the way,

193
00:15:36,769 --> 00:15:41,440
the police officer who helped us
in the forest 23 years ago

194
00:15:41,507 --> 00:15:42,908
is still working here, huh?

195
00:15:43,409 --> 00:15:45,010
Yeah. Chief Kosugi.

196
00:15:45,978 --> 00:15:46,912
You remember him?

197
00:15:46,979 --> 00:15:51,283
Yeah, because he was the first person
who helped me in the forest.

198
00:15:52,885 --> 00:15:53,786
What?

199
00:15:55,554 --> 00:15:56,522
What did you just say?

200
00:16:01,193 --> 00:16:02,428
Help!

201
00:16:06,532 --> 00:16:07,433
What's wrong?

202
00:16:08,334 --> 00:16:09,435
<i>What's wrong?</i>

203
00:16:09,501 --> 00:16:11,036
Um…

204
00:16:11,103 --> 00:16:11,937
What's the matter?

205
00:16:12,972 --> 00:16:15,841
- Um…
- What's wrong?

206
00:16:23,983 --> 00:16:24,817
Good morning.

207
00:16:24,883 --> 00:16:26,785
Things are pretty crazy.

208
00:16:26,852 --> 00:16:29,488
This is not a secret or anything,

209
00:16:29,555 --> 00:16:31,156
but Ms. Nara has been asking for you.

210
00:16:31,223 --> 00:16:33,959
Not just once, but two or three times!
What have you done?

211
00:16:34,560 --> 00:16:35,527
Because…

212
00:16:36,929 --> 00:16:37,763
Ms. Nara,

213
00:16:38,397 --> 00:16:39,431
I need to tell you something.

214
00:16:39,498 --> 00:16:42,401
INTERROGATION ROOM 1

215
00:17:02,855 --> 00:17:03,689
Come in.

216
00:17:03,756 --> 00:17:04,990
CHIEF'S OFFICE

217
00:17:05,057 --> 00:17:06,225
Excuse me.

218
00:17:06,291 --> 00:17:07,226
CHIEF KOSUGI

219
00:17:07,292 --> 00:17:08,293
Excuse me.

220
00:17:11,163 --> 00:17:14,199
The culprit turned out to be
Makiko Iwamoto?

221
00:17:14,933 --> 00:17:15,801
Yes.

222
00:17:18,437 --> 00:17:20,873
It must be tough for you, Tobina,
since she was your classmate.

223
00:17:21,774 --> 00:17:24,977
However,
I'm sure the late Officer Kiyohara

224
00:17:25,044 --> 00:17:28,714
is relieved that his missing gun
has been recovered.

225
00:17:30,015 --> 00:17:32,117
Please find out exactly how

226
00:17:32,651 --> 00:17:36,822
Makiko Iwamoto obtained the gun.

227
00:17:37,689 --> 00:17:41,727
There is something I would like
to confirm with you, Chief Kosugi,

228
00:17:41,794 --> 00:17:45,064
regarding how the gun was obtained.

229
00:17:45,564 --> 00:17:46,598
Me?

230
00:17:47,933 --> 00:17:50,569
Regarding the incident
that occurred 23 years ago,

231
00:17:50,636 --> 00:17:55,040
it was said at the time
that Oshima had an accomplice.

232
00:17:55,741 --> 00:17:57,976
Do you think there was an accomplice?

233
00:18:01,480 --> 00:18:04,650
The stolen 30 million yen was never found,

234
00:18:05,484 --> 00:18:08,120
and the investigation headquarters' view
at the time

235
00:18:08,887 --> 00:18:10,389
was that there was about

236
00:18:10,456 --> 00:18:13,258
an 80% chance that an accomplice
was involved.

237
00:18:13,325 --> 00:18:16,595
I believe without a doubt
there was an accomplice,

238
00:18:17,196 --> 00:18:19,998
and I think it was someone
within the police.

239
00:18:21,300 --> 00:18:22,534
Within the police?

240
00:18:23,302 --> 00:18:24,403
Yes.

241
00:18:27,439 --> 00:18:31,310
Please don't make
such accusations so lightly.

242
00:18:34,646 --> 00:18:39,118
Do you even have any proof?

243
00:18:40,319 --> 00:18:42,554
According to the investigation reports
from that time,

244
00:18:42,621 --> 00:18:46,158
multiple witnesses testified
that the robber

245
00:18:46,225 --> 00:18:49,161
fled towards the southern part
of the city.

246
00:18:49,695 --> 00:18:51,997
However, the robber was eventually found

247
00:18:52,064 --> 00:18:54,800
in Irohadai which is
in the northern part of the city.

248
00:18:56,902 --> 00:19:00,606
I believe this was due
to misleading reports from an accomplice.

249
00:19:02,841 --> 00:19:04,977
Posing as a regular citizen,

250
00:19:05,043 --> 00:19:07,713
the accomplice reported a sighting
of the robber

251
00:19:07,779 --> 00:19:10,282
and guided the police
to the southern part of the city.

252
00:19:11,717 --> 00:19:15,154
Meanwhile, in the unguarded
northern forest,

253
00:19:16,221 --> 00:19:19,625
the accomplice met up
with the perpetrator, Oshima.

254
00:19:21,160 --> 00:19:23,128
The purpose was probably

255
00:19:23,896 --> 00:19:25,297
to hand over the money.

256
00:19:31,103 --> 00:19:33,138
I think someone died.

257
00:19:34,540 --> 00:19:36,942
The bullet just happened
to hit that person.

258
00:19:37,009 --> 00:19:38,377
Yeah, that person died.

259
00:19:40,112 --> 00:19:41,079
Where's the money?

260
00:19:47,686 --> 00:19:49,221
We'll split the money later.

261
00:19:53,892 --> 00:19:55,661
Lay low for a while.

262
00:20:00,265 --> 00:20:01,266
Where's the gun?

263
00:20:03,035 --> 00:20:04,002
Where's the gun?

264
00:20:06,872 --> 00:20:08,707
Please give me more money.
This isn't enough.

265
00:20:12,711 --> 00:20:13,645
It's not bad.

266
00:20:13,712 --> 00:20:15,480
Yeah.

267
00:20:19,151 --> 00:20:21,753
If the accomplice was someone
in the police force,

268
00:20:21,820 --> 00:20:24,890
he could have informed Oshima
where the police were searching

269
00:20:24,957 --> 00:20:27,893
and skillfully guided him to the forest.

270
00:20:30,395 --> 00:20:31,863
They met in the forest,

271
00:20:34,032 --> 00:20:37,369
and the accomplice received money
from Oshima.

272
00:20:38,070 --> 00:20:41,139
Then, an unexpected incident occurred.

273
00:20:41,940 --> 00:20:43,642
The accomplice and Oshima were spotted

274
00:20:43,709 --> 00:20:46,078
by Officer Kazuo Kiyohara,
a local police officer

275
00:20:46,144 --> 00:20:49,181
who was also searching for the robber.

276
00:20:49,248 --> 00:20:50,882
- This isn't enough.
- Hey you two.

277
00:20:53,885 --> 00:20:54,920
It's the police.

278
00:20:55,520 --> 00:20:57,055
What are you guys doing there?

279
00:20:57,122 --> 00:21:00,559
Officer Kiyohara must have been surprised.

280
00:21:00,626 --> 00:21:03,128
After all,
he saw a man that looked like a robber,

281
00:21:03,729 --> 00:21:06,131
with none other than a police officer.

282
00:21:08,166 --> 00:21:09,668
Officer Kiyohara

283
00:21:10,269 --> 00:21:14,239
must have called out to the two of them,
trying to do his job.

284
00:21:15,207 --> 00:21:16,575
You, in the uniform,

285
00:21:17,876 --> 00:21:19,111
what are you doing?

286
00:21:22,547 --> 00:21:25,417
Following that, Officer Kiyohara

287
00:21:25,917 --> 00:21:29,187
was forced to fire two shots

288
00:21:29,688 --> 00:21:31,523
as a warning.

289
00:21:33,225 --> 00:21:34,660
Drop the gun!

290
00:21:42,234 --> 00:21:43,935
Freeze!

291
00:21:54,379 --> 00:21:56,715
Are you a police officer?

292
00:21:57,215 --> 00:21:58,216
Yes.

293
00:22:00,385 --> 00:22:01,620
Are you the section chief?

294
00:22:02,220 --> 00:22:03,055
And you are?

295
00:22:03,989 --> 00:22:05,791
I'm stationed at Irohadai.

296
00:22:05,857 --> 00:22:07,592
My name is Kazuo Kiyohara--

297
00:22:13,465 --> 00:22:14,700
The accomplice

298
00:22:15,434 --> 00:22:19,171
pointed the modified gun
at Officer Kiyohara

299
00:22:19,237 --> 00:22:20,939
and shot him dead.

300
00:22:30,882 --> 00:22:32,217
But then

301
00:22:33,118 --> 00:22:35,420
an unexpected person appears.

302
00:22:39,925 --> 00:22:43,495
Junichi Tobina, a sixth-grader.

303
00:22:45,731 --> 00:22:46,998
But then

304
00:22:47,499 --> 00:22:49,801
an unexpected person appears.

305
00:22:54,339 --> 00:22:57,976
Junichi Tobina, a sixth-grader.

306
00:22:58,677 --> 00:23:02,714
<i>The accomplice</i>
<i>quickly hid in the shade of a nearby tree.</i>

307
00:23:03,315 --> 00:23:05,250
The young boy arrived at the scene,

308
00:23:05,317 --> 00:23:08,353
and when he saw Officer Kiyohara's body,

309
00:23:08,420 --> 00:23:10,188
he realized what had happened.

310
00:23:13,358 --> 00:23:16,328
Then he saw Oshima.

311
00:23:25,270 --> 00:23:28,740
The boy then did something surprising.

312
00:23:28,807 --> 00:23:31,476
He picked up Officer Kiyohara's gun

313
00:23:32,677 --> 00:23:35,647
and pointed it at Oshima.

314
00:23:36,448 --> 00:23:40,485
The accomplice, who was watching
the scene unfold, must have been shocked.

315
00:23:45,390 --> 00:23:47,058
<i>However, that accomplice</i>

316
00:23:50,562 --> 00:23:52,931
aimed the gun at Oshima.

317
00:24:06,845 --> 00:24:07,846
<i>Then you</i>

318
00:24:10,949 --> 00:24:15,253
shot and killed Oshima
with your service pistol.

319
00:24:18,156 --> 00:24:19,891
You shot him,

320
00:24:20,425 --> 00:24:21,660
didn't you, Chief Kosugi?

321
00:24:26,531 --> 00:24:28,767
That's an interesting theory,

322
00:24:28,834 --> 00:24:31,102
but there's no objective facts.

323
00:24:39,945 --> 00:24:41,413
I have just that.

324
00:24:56,962 --> 00:24:59,598
The gun that Makiko Iwamoto was carrying

325
00:25:00,198 --> 00:25:05,003
was not Officer Kiyohara's gun
that went missing 23 years ago.

326
00:25:07,572 --> 00:25:08,507
Do you have proof?

327
00:25:10,141 --> 00:25:11,576
The number of remaining bullets.

328
00:25:14,179 --> 00:25:15,580
As you know,

329
00:25:15,647 --> 00:25:18,650
the New Nambu is a five-shot revolver.

330
00:25:19,351 --> 00:25:22,654
Two warning shots
were fired by Officer Kiyohara.

331
00:25:23,622 --> 00:25:26,725
Twenty-three years later,

332
00:25:26,791 --> 00:25:29,661
another bullet was fired to kill Sakuma.

333
00:25:30,428 --> 00:25:33,498
That leaves two remaining bullets.

334
00:25:33,565 --> 00:25:36,501
And if Detective Tobina had fired a shot,

335
00:25:36,568 --> 00:25:39,738
there would be one less bullet.

336
00:25:40,872 --> 00:25:41,940
However,

337
00:25:42,641 --> 00:25:45,677
the gun Makiko Iwamoto had
in her possession

338
00:25:46,878 --> 00:25:49,114
had three bullets left.

339
00:25:50,882 --> 00:25:54,286
In other words,
that gun is not Officer Kiyohara's.

340
00:25:58,990 --> 00:26:01,660
You switched the guns, right?

341
00:26:41,032 --> 00:26:42,267
<i>Then</i>

342
00:26:43,535 --> 00:26:45,870
you took a big detour,

343
00:26:46,571 --> 00:26:50,241
met Naoto Sakuma in the forest,
and rescued him.

344
00:26:53,979 --> 00:26:55,180
Help!

345
00:26:58,917 --> 00:26:59,918
What's the matter?

346
00:27:01,653 --> 00:27:04,589
As the person in charge
of equipment management,

347
00:27:04,656 --> 00:27:07,492
you falsified the data
in the equipment ledger.

348
00:27:08,526 --> 00:27:10,161
<i>In order to match the rifling marks,</i>

349
00:27:10,228 --> 00:27:13,198
<i>you switched the equipment numbers</i>
<i>of the gun</i>

350
00:27:13,798 --> 00:27:17,235
that belonged to Officer Kiyohara,
with the gun you used to shoot Oshima.

351
00:27:20,338 --> 00:27:21,473
Believe it or not,

352
00:27:21,539 --> 00:27:24,376
when I checked the archives
at the prefectural police headquarters,

353
00:27:24,876 --> 00:27:26,111
I found

354
00:27:26,778 --> 00:27:30,548
that the original paper copy
was still available.

355
00:27:32,717 --> 00:27:36,287
This is the document before you changed
the equipment numbers.

356
00:27:58,410 --> 00:28:00,345
This is the prefectural police
headquarters.

357
00:28:00,412 --> 00:28:02,213
Chief Kosugi of Mitsuba Police Station,

358
00:28:02,280 --> 00:28:04,749
you're under arrest
for the murder 23 years ago.

359
00:28:04,816 --> 00:28:07,018
- What?
- This is the arrest warrant.

360
00:28:07,085 --> 00:28:08,053
Chief.

361
00:28:13,625 --> 00:28:14,993
Oh, boy.

362
00:28:16,061 --> 00:28:18,163
- Let's go.
- Wait.

363
00:28:18,663 --> 00:28:22,133
I want to correct and clarify one thing.

364
00:28:22,667 --> 00:28:25,737
I wasn't the accomplice.

365
00:28:26,538 --> 00:28:29,007
I don't want to be lumped together
with Oshima.

366
00:28:29,507 --> 00:28:31,743
I was the mastermind.

367
00:28:31,810 --> 00:28:33,311
Come.

368
00:28:40,785 --> 00:28:42,487
- Tobina.
- Stop it, Tobina!

369
00:28:44,022 --> 00:28:45,056
Hey!

370
00:28:45,890 --> 00:28:47,492
<i>Why are you alive,</i>

371
00:28:48,893 --> 00:28:50,328
<i>while Pops is dead?</i>

372
00:28:50,929 --> 00:28:52,630
<i>- Why? Why?</i>
<i>- Calm down.</i>

373
00:28:52,697 --> 00:28:54,332
Why?!

374
00:28:56,434 --> 00:28:58,303
Why?!

375
00:28:59,437 --> 00:29:00,605
<i>Calm down!</i>

376
00:29:02,841 --> 00:29:04,442
<i>Calm down!</i>

377
00:29:04,509 --> 00:29:05,877
MITSUBA KENDO CHAMPIONSHIP

378
00:29:08,847 --> 00:29:09,781
Have you ever had a dream

379
00:29:12,584 --> 00:29:14,486
about someone you killed… or who died?

380
00:29:17,922 --> 00:29:19,190
Nope.

381
00:29:20,492 --> 00:29:22,060
Thanks to you guys,

382
00:29:22,694 --> 00:29:24,362
I'll be on death row now.

383
00:29:25,463 --> 00:29:26,898
I'll appear in your dreams.

384
00:29:30,268 --> 00:29:32,370
I shouldn't have arrested you.

385
00:29:34,038 --> 00:29:36,207
I should've killed you with my own hands.

386
00:29:39,778 --> 00:29:42,080
Just calm down!

387
00:29:52,190 --> 00:29:55,460
Wow, it's so shocking.

388
00:29:55,527 --> 00:29:58,663
Who would've thought
that Chief Kosugi was the culprit?

389
00:29:59,898 --> 00:30:00,732
Yeah.

390
00:30:02,367 --> 00:30:04,803
Also, there's a rumor going around

391
00:30:05,303 --> 00:30:07,138
that Ms. Nara screamed?

392
00:30:08,706 --> 00:30:10,341
Yeah, she did.

393
00:30:10,408 --> 00:30:11,876
Why did she scream?

394
00:30:19,884 --> 00:30:21,152
I don't know either.

395
00:30:22,720 --> 00:30:24,189
Oh man.

396
00:30:24,255 --> 00:30:27,225
I bet she couldn't forgive the fact
that a police officer committed murder.

397
00:30:27,292 --> 00:30:29,060
That's not it, Detective Inoue.

398
00:30:31,763 --> 00:30:32,597
I'm Nagai.

399
00:30:36,801 --> 00:30:40,104
Do you know who the first victim was
in the incident

400
00:30:40,171 --> 00:30:41,906
23 years ago?

401
00:30:44,042 --> 00:30:46,611
The citizen who was hit by a stray bullet
at the bank, right?

402
00:30:53,351 --> 00:30:55,019
- Are you all right?
- Kurihara, are you all right?

403
00:30:55,086 --> 00:30:56,721
- Someone, call the ambulance!
- Kurihara.

404
00:30:56,788 --> 00:30:58,289
<i>Akio Kurihara.</i>

405
00:30:59,357 --> 00:31:01,159
He was my fiancé.

406
00:31:34,626 --> 00:31:36,628
- Good morning.
- Good morning.

407
00:31:39,063 --> 00:31:41,466
- Good morning.
- Good morning.

408
00:31:42,800 --> 00:31:43,801
Were you able to sleep?

409
00:31:49,440 --> 00:31:51,676
You won't have nightmares anymore, huh?

410
00:32:01,352 --> 00:32:02,220
I'm glad.

411
00:32:11,930 --> 00:32:14,532
Hiromi, you were the only one
who didn't ask me

412
00:32:17,168 --> 00:32:19,771
about my nightmares
or try to talk about the future.

413
00:32:21,639 --> 00:32:24,642
That helped me to feel at ease.

414
00:32:24,709 --> 00:32:25,543
Is that right?

415
00:32:25,610 --> 00:32:26,511
Yeah.

416
00:32:28,980 --> 00:32:31,683
I felt like it was okay for me to be here.

417
00:32:32,850 --> 00:32:34,686
I felt that I was accepted.

418
00:32:40,658 --> 00:32:42,560
Should we talk about the future?

419
00:32:47,665 --> 00:32:49,000
What do you want to do?

420
00:32:52,136 --> 00:32:55,873
This time, Makiko will have to bear
the guilt of having killed someone.

421
00:32:57,442 --> 00:32:58,476
I

422
00:32:59,444 --> 00:33:01,946
don't know what Makiko's verdict will be,

423
00:33:07,518 --> 00:33:08,920
but I want to support her.

424
00:33:16,027 --> 00:33:17,962
Just be honest and say that you like her.

425
00:33:23,634 --> 00:33:24,602
Okay.

426
00:33:28,606 --> 00:33:30,541
I'll be leaving this town.

427
00:33:41,219 --> 00:33:42,220
Bye.

428
00:33:43,121 --> 00:33:45,223
Bye. Thank you.

429
00:34:02,473 --> 00:34:03,474
Junichi.

430
00:34:11,649 --> 00:34:12,750
I love you.

431
00:34:14,652 --> 00:34:17,488
Spin me around.

432
00:34:18,122 --> 00:34:19,624
Since this is the last time.

433
00:34:21,592 --> 00:34:22,760
<i>Makiko Iwamoto</i>

434
00:34:23,327 --> 00:34:25,296
has been indicted
and next it will be the trial.

435
00:34:26,631 --> 00:34:27,598
Yes.

436
00:34:27,665 --> 00:34:29,934
Our buddy partnership
will be dissolved, huh?

437
00:34:31,169 --> 00:34:33,037
I'm so grateful to you, Ms. Nara.

438
00:34:33,838 --> 00:34:35,306
Thank you very much.

439
00:34:37,275 --> 00:34:39,977
Just like you,
whenever I tried to move forward,

440
00:34:40,044 --> 00:34:44,315
I found myself
being pulled back to 23 years ago.

441
00:34:45,083 --> 00:34:47,018
That's how it was for me
the last 23 years.

442
00:34:50,388 --> 00:34:53,958
In your case, you found out
that you never killed anyone.

443
00:34:54,592 --> 00:34:56,160
But in my case,

444
00:34:56,227 --> 00:34:59,163
the fact that my fiancé died
remains unchanged.

445
00:35:01,132 --> 00:35:02,133
However,

446
00:35:03,000 --> 00:35:07,472
I realized that maybe
I'm also making wrong assumptions,

447
00:35:07,538 --> 00:35:09,040
so I thought about it a bit.

448
00:35:10,041 --> 00:35:10,975
I see.

449
00:35:12,877 --> 00:35:14,078
I

450
00:35:15,079 --> 00:35:17,615
will never find a man
who's as good as Kurihara.

451
00:35:20,184 --> 00:35:21,119
What do you say to that?

452
00:35:25,256 --> 00:35:26,424
That's an assumption.

453
00:35:27,525 --> 00:35:28,459
Really?

454
00:35:28,960 --> 00:35:29,794
Yes.

455
00:35:31,262 --> 00:35:32,797
That's definitely an assumption.

456
00:35:36,701 --> 00:35:37,902
Excuse me.

457
00:35:37,969 --> 00:35:39,537
May I sit here?

458
00:35:39,604 --> 00:35:40,438
Sure, of course.

459
00:35:40,505 --> 00:35:41,672
Thank you.

460
00:35:47,211 --> 00:35:48,045
Yes?

461
00:35:50,181 --> 00:35:51,315
It's salted salmon.

462
00:35:52,150 --> 00:35:53,784
Oh, salted salmon?

463
00:35:54,485 --> 00:35:55,686
I like that.

464
00:35:57,989 --> 00:35:59,790
Do you come here often?

465
00:36:00,925 --> 00:36:02,960
Once in a while.

466
00:36:17,041 --> 00:36:18,576
We won't be able to see each other
for a while.

467
00:36:24,982 --> 00:36:26,284
Masaki

468
00:36:28,553 --> 00:36:30,655
is still unable to leave the house,

469
00:36:32,823 --> 00:36:33,991
but he's fine.

470
00:36:34,625 --> 00:36:36,327
He's eating all his meals every day.

471
00:36:47,939 --> 00:36:48,806
You know…

472
00:36:51,375 --> 00:36:53,744
<i>a long time ago, when I was moving away,</i>

473
00:36:54,712 --> 00:36:56,814
<i>you said you'd see me off,</i>
<i>but I was rude to you.</i>

474
00:36:57,748 --> 00:36:59,116
I'm sorry.

475
00:37:04,522 --> 00:37:07,124
When I was 20, I was in Yokohama too,

476
00:37:10,895 --> 00:37:12,496
and I actually knew

477
00:37:12,997 --> 00:37:16,367
that you were working part-time
at that cafe.

478
00:37:29,380 --> 00:37:31,082
<i>I was never able to tell you</i>
<i>that I like you.</i>

479
00:37:39,023 --> 00:37:40,091
Makiko,

480
00:37:45,062 --> 00:37:45,963
I love you.

481
00:38:14,258 --> 00:38:15,226
Keisuke.

482
00:38:15,726 --> 00:38:16,560
Yeah?

483
00:38:19,964 --> 00:38:21,532
When Makiko comes back,

484
00:38:23,501 --> 00:38:24,502
I'm planning on asking her

485
00:38:26,837 --> 00:38:28,339
to live with me.

486
00:38:30,941 --> 00:38:32,209
With Masaki too.

487
00:38:35,246 --> 00:38:36,681
Why are you reporting this to me?

488
00:38:38,349 --> 00:38:40,451
It's for Makiko and Masaki to decide.

489
00:38:41,285 --> 00:38:44,588
I have no say in who they live with.

490
00:38:45,456 --> 00:38:46,290
What about you, Naoto?

491
00:38:46,924 --> 00:38:47,958
You have anything to say?

492
00:38:51,228 --> 00:38:52,196
No.

493
00:38:54,565 --> 00:38:56,200
I think Maki will be happy.

494
00:39:03,274 --> 00:39:05,009
It still pisses me off though.

495
00:39:08,813 --> 00:39:11,115
My dad became Pops to you,

496
00:39:11,182 --> 00:39:13,617
and now you want to live with my son?

497
00:39:15,319 --> 00:39:18,589
My dad loved you,
and my son is attached to you too.

498
00:39:18,656 --> 00:39:20,091
Of course I don't like that.

499
00:39:22,660 --> 00:39:23,494
And now

500
00:39:24,362 --> 00:39:26,530
you're going to live with Makiko?

501
00:39:29,033 --> 00:39:32,036
I wouldn't be able to handle Makiko
as she carries the burden of her crime.

502
00:39:32,670 --> 00:39:33,838
What's more,

503
00:39:33,904 --> 00:39:35,573
if I knew back then that Makiko

504
00:39:35,639 --> 00:39:37,908
had been raped,
I wouldn't have been able to handle it.

505
00:39:39,310 --> 00:39:42,346
But I'm sure you would've been able to,
Junichi.

506
00:39:42,413 --> 00:39:44,215
You keep popping up in my head like that.

507
00:39:45,282 --> 00:39:47,485
I'm sick and tired
of comparing myself to you!

508
00:39:49,553 --> 00:39:51,021
What am I, chopped liver?

509
00:39:52,623 --> 00:39:54,225
How is that my fault?

510
00:40:00,464 --> 00:40:02,233
It pisses me off.

511
00:40:07,138 --> 00:40:08,239
Junichi.

512
00:40:10,741 --> 00:40:12,410
Please help support Masaki.

513
00:40:23,587 --> 00:40:24,755
All right.

514
00:40:30,027 --> 00:40:31,762
ONE YEAR LATER

515
00:40:31,829 --> 00:40:33,097
- Venezuela.
- Caracas.

516
00:40:33,831 --> 00:40:34,665
Mongolia.

517
00:40:35,299 --> 00:40:36,300
Ulaanbaatar.

518
00:40:36,367 --> 00:40:37,635
Nice.

519
00:40:39,370 --> 00:40:40,404
India.

520
00:40:41,205 --> 00:40:44,175
- What?
- You're making no sense.

521
00:40:44,241 --> 00:40:45,242
Why?

522
00:40:53,050 --> 00:40:54,452
Yes, please proceed with that.

523
00:40:55,719 --> 00:40:59,657
So far, no major issues
have been raised by the inspection agency.

524
00:41:00,558 --> 00:41:03,661
We are also finalizing the preliminary
exterior design plans as well.

525
00:41:03,727 --> 00:41:04,328
JUNICHI TOBINA

526
00:41:04,395 --> 00:41:05,396
By concentrating

527
00:41:06,030 --> 00:41:08,265
construction vehicles on the south side,

528
00:41:08,933 --> 00:41:10,067
we can reduce the…

529
00:41:10,134 --> 00:41:11,368
<i>Makiko's sentence has been decided.</i>

530
00:41:12,403 --> 00:41:14,271
<i>Three years imprisonment for murder.</i>

531
00:41:15,272 --> 00:41:16,407
<i>Five years suspension.</i>

532
00:41:41,499 --> 00:41:44,902
KANAGAWA DETENTION CENTER

533
00:41:59,750 --> 00:42:00,885
You came?

534
00:42:10,127 --> 00:42:10,995
Let's go.

535
00:42:18,202 --> 00:42:20,704
<i>The crimes we sealed in the past</i>
<i>were brought to light.</i>

536
00:42:22,573 --> 00:42:23,908
<i>Our lives were</i>

537
00:42:25,376 --> 00:42:26,911
<i>shaken up.</i>

538
00:42:33,384 --> 00:42:34,585
Junichi.

539
00:42:35,819 --> 00:42:36,654
Yeah?

540
00:42:39,823 --> 00:42:41,091
Thank you.

541
00:42:51,902 --> 00:42:53,003
Hey.

542
00:42:55,339 --> 00:42:56,173
Yeah?

543
00:42:57,808 --> 00:42:59,376
Have you kissed anyone before?

544
00:43:06,283 --> 00:43:07,318
What?

545
00:43:09,887 --> 00:43:12,056
What is it all of a sudden?

546
00:43:12,623 --> 00:43:13,624
<i>Right then,</i>

547
00:43:15,025 --> 00:43:16,694
<i>the door to the future…</i>

548
00:43:20,731 --> 00:43:21,932
<i>softly opened.</i>

549
00:44:08,946 --> 00:44:10,748
THIS DRAMA IS A FICTION

550
00:44:10,814 --> 00:44:12,683
Subtitle translation by: Lili Morita
